  "If a radioactive isotope has a half-life of 10 years and you start with 100 g, how much remains after 30 years?": "",
  "50 g (after 1 half-life: 100→50 at 10 years)": "",
  "30 g (proportional: 100 × 30/100 remaining)": "",
  "25 g (after 2 half-lives: 100→50→25 at 20 yr)": "",
  "12.5 g (after 3 half-lives: 100→50→25→12.5)": "",
  "30 years / 10 years = 3 half-lives. 100 g → 50 g → 25 g → 12.5 g. After 3 half-lives, 100 × (1/2)³ = 12.5 g.": "",
  "The half-life of carbon-14 is 5730 years. A sample originally had 80 g. How much C-14 remains after 11,460 years?": "",
  "10 g (after 3 half-lives: 80→40→20→10)": "",
  "80 g (no decay occurs over this time period)": "",
  "40 g (after 1 half-life: 80→40 at 5730 yr)": "",
  "20 g (after 2 half-lives: 80→40→20)": "",
  "11,460 / 5730 = 2 half-lives. 80 g × (1/2)² = 80/4 = 20 g.": "",
  "Radiocarbon dating uses C-14 because:": "",
  "C-14 has a half-life of 1 second, so it decays quickly enough to measure in a laboratory within hours": "",
  "All carbon isotopes decay equally fast, making any carbon isotope suitable for reliable age dating": "",
  "All living organisms absorb C-14 from the atmosphere; after death, C-14 decays at a known rate (t₁/₂=5730 yr)": "",
  "C-14 is stable and never decays, so its concentration stays constant in living and dead organisms": "",
  "While alive, organisms maintain a constant C-14/C-12 ratio. After death, C-14 decays (β⁻, t₁/₂=5730 yr). Measuring the ratio determines age.": "",
